                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRCOLOGNEPROSE_MSVIII" target="_blank"><span class="title-essay-JRCOLOGNEPROSE_MSVIII">&#x201C;Cologne&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 61r; prose, first paragraph only, annotated as &#x201C;fragment&#x201D; by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>; titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JROHTHEMORNLOOKEDBRIGHT" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JROHTHEMORNLOOKEDBRIGHT">&#x201C;Oh the morn looked bright over hill and dale&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 61r&#x2013;61v; poem, untitled, lines numbered 778&#x2013;809 by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>; entitled by editors of the Library Edition, not <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, as &#x201C;The Black Forest&#x201D;).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRITWASAWIDESTRETCHYSWEEPESSAY" target="_blank"><span class="title-essay-JRITWASAWIDESTRETCHYSWEEPPOEM">&#x201C;It was a wide stretchy sweep&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 62r; prose, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRBRUSSELSPROSE1_MSVIII" target="_blank"><span class="title-essay-JRBRUSSELSPROSE1_MSVIII">&#x201C;Part of Brussels&#x201D; &#x005B;part 1&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 62r&#x2013;62v; prose, from &#x201C;Brussels is a lovely, a queenlike city from a distance&#x201D; to &#x201C;for circumnavigating, for <span class="del">traversing</span>&#x201D;; titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#OHSOFTLYBLEWPOEM" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JROHSOFTLYBLEW">&#x201C;Oh softly blew the mounting breeze&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 62v; poem, untitled, lines numbered 810&#x2013;22 by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>; entitled by editors of the Library Edition, not by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, as &#x201C;Chiavenna&#x201D;).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRBRUSSELSPROSE1_MSVIII" target="_blank"><span class="title-essay-JRBRUSSELSPROSE1_MSVIII">&#x201C;Part of Brussels&#x201D; &#x005B;part 2&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 63r&#x2013;63v; prose, from &#x201C;perambulating. Oh woe to the walker&#x201D; to &#x201C;Oh tread on it softly&#x201D;; untitled, but clearly a continuation of titled prose section begun on pp. 62r&#x2013;62v, with the prose resumed on pp. 63r&#x2013;63v to the end of the passage as fair&#x2010;copied in ).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#LAGODICOMOPOEM" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRLAGODICOMOPOEM">&#x201C;Lago di Como&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 63v&#x2013;64r; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, lines numbered 823&#x2013;63 by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRGENOAPOEM" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRGENOAPOEM">&#x201C;Genoa&#x201D; (&#x201C;Of various trees a vista green&#x201D;)</span></a> (pp. 64r&#x2013;64v; poem, untitled, lines numbered 864&#x2013;89 by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>). 
                                    While <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> does not entitle these lines here, 
                                    he later incorporates a version of these lines into a draft of a poem that he entitles &#x201C;Genoa&#x201D; 
                                    <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRGENOA2" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRGENOA">&#x201C;Genoa&#x201D; (&#x201C;Now rouse the ho. For Genoa straight&#x201D;)</span></a>.
                                    Nothing definitively proves that, at this point of composition, <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> identified these lines with the place name, <span class="placeName-GENOA">Genoa</span>, or destined these lines for a later, fuller composition of that name. 
                                    Asterisks follow the final line of the draft here, a symbol that appears to correspond to asterisks attached to the corresponding line in 
                                    <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRGENOA3" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRGENOA">&#x201C;Genoa&#x201D; (&#x201C;Now rouse the ho. For Genoa straight&#x201D;)</span></a>, 
                                    but <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> could have returned and added the asterisks here when deciding to insert these lines into the later composition.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRITWASANEVEOFSUMMERMILD1" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRITWASANEVEOFSUMMERMILD">&#x201C;It was an eve of summer, mild&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 64v&#x2013;65r; poem, untitled, lines numbered 890&#x2013;920 by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>; 
                                    combined with 8 lines . . . and entitled by the editors of the Library Edition, not by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, as &#x201C;Lago Maggiore&#x201D;).
                     </li> 
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRAIXLACHAPELLE" target="_blank"><span class="title-prose-JRAIXLACHAPELLE">&#x201C;Aix la Chapelle&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 65r&#x2013;66r; prose, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>). 
                                    On 65v, at the end of the sixth paragraph, after the word &#x201C;monarch,&#x201D; appears in draft the one&#x2010;word sentence: &#x201C;Wake&#x2014;.&#x201D; This sentence appears neither in the fair copy of &#x201C;Aix la Chapelle,&#x201D; in <a href="../apparatuses/msix_apparatus.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">MS IX</a>, 
                                    nor in the version printed in the Library Edition. Since this sentence falls at the bottom of 65v, it may have served <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> as a marker of some kind, interrupting (or egging on) his rough&#x2010;drafting. 
                                    On the following recto, 66r, the remainder of the prose passage is drafted (from &#x201C;Saw Charlemagnes easy chair . . .&#x201D; to &#x201C;Goodnight&#x201D;). 
                                    The remainder of 66r is filled with two rough sketches in ink&#x2014;one of mountains (including a volcano?), and one of palaces and boats on a canal, probably a <span class="placeName-VENICE">Venetian</span> subject&#x2014;bearing no resemblance 
                                    to any of the vignettes extant in <a href="../apparatuses/msix_apparatus.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">MS IX</a>. Another curiousity respecting this passage is the numbering, which, uniquely for a prose passage, shows a number 100 
                                    parallel with the final line (66r). Following this, in the margin at the right of the drawings, appear the numbers 925 and 930. The latter numbering. which is continuous with 890&#x2013;920 assigned to 
                                    the preceding item, <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRITWASANEVEOFSUMMERMILD2" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRITWASANEVEOFSUMMERMILD2">&#x201C;It was an eve of summer, mild&#x201D;</span></a> (64v&#x2013;65r), evidently awaited 
                                    a stint of poetry, but <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> intervened with the sketches&#x2014;even draing the <span class="placeName-VENICE">Venetian</span> scene over top of the number 930. When poetry does resume on the verso (66v), 
                                    <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> does not begin numbering from 921, where he actually left off at the end of 
                                    <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRITWASANEVEOFSUMMERMILD3" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRITWASANEVEOFSUMMERMILD3">&#x201C;It was an eve of summer, mild&#x201D;</span></a>, 
                                    but from 939&#x2014;as if he did use &#x201C;925&#x201D; and &#x201C;930&#x201D; to number verse lines on 66r.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRHEIDELBERG1" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRHEIDELBERG1">&#x201C;Smiling from those bright rays kiss&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;Heidelberg&#x201D; poem, part 1&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 66v&#x2013;67r; poem, untitled, lines numbered 939&#x2013;68 by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>). 
                                        Although not titled in this place, these lines belong with lines headed &#x201C;Continuation Heidelberg&#x201D; below, an arrangement confirmed by the text of the poem as fair&#x2010;copied in <a href="../apparatuses/msix_apparatus.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">MS IX</a>.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRTRADITIONSOFTHERHINE" target="_blank"><span class="title-prose-JRTRADITIONSOFTHERHINE">&#x201C;The traditions of the Rhine&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 67r&#x2013;67v; prose, untitled; entitled by editors of Library Edition, not by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, as &#x201C;The Rhine&#x201D;).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JREHRENBREITSTEIN" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JREHRENBREITSTEIN">&#x201C;Oh warmly down the sunbeams fell&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;Ehrenbreitstein&#x201D; poem&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 67v&#x2013;69r; poem, untitled, lines numbered 973&#x2013;1081 by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>). 
                                        These lines are entitled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> in <a href="../apparatuses/msix_apparatus.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">MS IX</a>, not in MS VIII, as &#x201C;Ehrenbreitstein.&#x201D; Note that the line numbering begins, not with 969 as would be expected following 
                                        <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRHEIDELBERG1" target="_blank">&#x201C;<span class="title-poem-JRHEIDELBERG1">Smiling from those bright rays kiss&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;Heidelberg&#x201D; poem, part 1&#x005D;</span></a>, but with 973.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRHEIDELBERG2" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRHEIDELBERG2">&#x201C;Continuation Heidelberg&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;Heidelberg&#x201D; poem, part 2&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 69r&#x2013;70v; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, lines numbered 1083&#x2013;1155)..
                                    A continuation of <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRHEIDELBERG1" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRHEIDELBERG1">&#x201C;Smiling from those bright rays kiss&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;Heidelberg&#x201D; poem, part 1&#x005D;</span></a>, above. 
                                    This segment begins with the variant lines as given in <a href="../bibiliography/bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-work-JRWORKSLE"><span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, <i>Works</i></span></a>, 2:362 n. 1; 
                                        in MS VIII, these lines are scored through. Following these deleted lines, the text of the poem in MS VIII accords with the fair copy in <a href="../apparatuses/msix_apparatus.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">MS IX</a>.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRSCHAFFHAUSEN" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRSCHAFFHAUSEN">&#x201C;Schaffhausen&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 70v; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, lines numbered 1148&#x2013;59; 
                                        entitled by editors of Library Edition as &#x201C;Entrance to Schaffhausen&#x201D;). The final punctuation of this poem is a comma, suggesting that this draft poem may be incomplete. 
                                    Another anomaly is <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin&#x02BC;s</span> line numbering, which overlaps with that for 
                                        . 
                                        Also, his notation of line numbers for &#x201C;Schaffhausen&#x201D; is inconsistent with his practice elsewhere, in that he tags a line with the odd number 1151, instead of his usual interval of 5. 
                                    Since the manuscript gives every appearance of <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> working steadily and sequentially, with no crowding of lines indicating a collision of numbering systems&#x2014;such 
                                        as might have arisen from his squeezing lines into a space preceding a pre&#x2010;existing &#x201C;Schaffhausen&#x201D;&#x2014;the inconsistent numbering may represent <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin&#x02BC;s</span> deliberate attempt 
                                    to correct an earlier anomaly, such as that noted respecting 
                                        <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JREHRENBREITSTEIN" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JREHRENBREITSTEIN">&#x201C;Oh warmly down the sunbeams fell&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;Ehrenbreitstein&#x201D; poem&#x005D;</span></a>.
                     </li>  
                     
                  </ul>
                  
               </p>        
               
               <p> 
                            In the remaining stint of Contents, section <i>b</i>, the composition of 
                            <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php" target="_blank">Account of a Tour on the Continent</a> 
                            is not continuous, its sections becoming mixed with other material&#x2014;some of it certainly belonging to other works, 
                            some of it ambiguous respecting <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin&#x02BC;s</span> intention.
               </p>
               
               <p>
                  
                  <ul>
                     <span class="head">List <i>b</i>.2</span>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_lake_smiled_sweetly.php#JRLAKESMILEDSWEETLY" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRLAKESMILEDSWEETLY">&#x201C;The lake smiled sweetly, and the boy&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 70v&#x2013;71r; poem, untitled). 
                                        The editors of the Library Edition omitted this poem from their version of 
                                        <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php" target="_blank">Account of a Tour on the Continent</a>, 
                                        perhaps because <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> did not include the poem&#x02BC;s dozen lines in his system of line numbering&#x2014;which jumps from 1159, 
                                        at the end of the preceding section, <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRSCHAFFHAUSEN" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRSCHAFFHAUSEN">&#x201C;Schaffhausen&#x201D;</span></a>, 
                                        to 1160, at the start of the following section. As remarked earlier, however, the significance of <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin&#x02BC;s</span> line numbering is obscure, and the numbering is not always consistent in itself. 
                                        No other factor argues for excluding the poem; its style and content of the poem appears consistent with other verse for the &#x201C;Account,&#x201D; 
                                        and the manuscript shows no crowding or change in compositional proecedure&#x2014;a line space neatly dividing the poem from the poem &#x201C;Schaffhausen&#x201D; preceding it, 
                                        and another line space dividing it from the poem following.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRNOTSUCHTHENIGHT" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRNOTSUCHTHENIGHT">&#x201C;Not such the night whose stormy might&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                        (p. 71r; poem, untitled, lines numbered 1160&#x2013;82; entitled by editors of Library Edition, not by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, as &#x201C;Evening at Chamouni&#x201D;). 
                                        A possible reason for <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin&#x02BC;s</span> passing over numbering the lines of <a href="../apparatuses/the_lake_smiled_sweetly.php#JRLAKESMILEDSWEETLY" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRLAKESMILEDSWEETLY">&#x201C;The lake smiled sweetly, and the boy&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                        is that he intended to connect the beginning of &#x201C;Not such the night whose stormy might&#x201D; (1160) with the end (1159) of 
                                        <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRSCHAFFHAUSEN" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRSCHAFFHAUSEN">&#x201C;Schaffhausen&#x201D;</span></a>&#x2014;that is, he meant the present poem as a continuation of &#x201C;Schaffhausen,&#x201D; 
                                        the draft of which ends with a comma, not with closing punctuation.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#ITISSAIDTHATFRENCH" target="_blank">&#x201C;It is said that French will carry you over all Europe&#x201D;</a> 
                                        (pp. 71v&#x2013;72r; prose, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRMOSTBEAUTIFULPATHS" target="_blank"><span class="title-prose-JRMOSTBEAUTIFULPATHS">&#x201C;Most beautiful are the paths&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 72r; prose, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_vintage_apparatus.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">&#x201C;The Vintage&#x201D;</a> (pp. 72r&#x2013;72v; 21 lines, untitled). 
                                        Incomplete here, the composition is resumed on 77r, below. 
                                        With &#x201C;The Vintage,&#x201D; is is clear that, at this point in MS VIII, <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> departed temporarily from composition of the &#x201C;Account&#x201D; 
                                        to prepare birthday odes for <span class="date-1834-05-10">his father&#x02BC;s May 1834 anniversary</span>. 
                                        The manuscript shows no signs of crowding, but it is possible that <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> had skipped ahead in MS VIII to compose &#x201C;The Vintage,&#x201D; &#x201C;The Address,&#x201D; and &#x201C;The Crystal Hunter,&#x201D; 
                                        and later wrapped the continuing &#x201C;Account&#x201D; material around these drafts. He may have begun &#x201C;The Crystal Hunter&#x201D; in the middle of 72v and inserted the first 21 lines of &#x201C;The Vintage&#x201D; 
                                        in the blank space preceding &#x201C;The Crystal Hunter,&#x201D; or he may have started composition of &#x201C;The Vintage&#x201D; and temporarily halted it to work on &#x201C;The Crystal Hunter.&#x201D; 
                                        More intriguing than the order of composition is whether <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> meant &#x201C;The Vintage&#x201D; to belong to the &#x201C;Account&#x201D; or to the <span class="date-1834-05-10">1834 birthday</span> odes&#x2014;or to stand on its own as a separate composition. 
                                        The editors of the Library Edition evidently did not know what to make of the poem and left it unpublished. 
                                        Indeed, while the opening description in &#x201C;The Vintage&#x201D; of grape harvesting on the Continent might connect the poem with the &#x201C;Account,&#x201D; 
                                        its comic quarrel between casks of wine in a cellar seems out of keeping with the topographical work 
                                        as do the poem&#x2019;s octameter couplets.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_crystal_hunter_apparatus.php#JRCRYSTALHUNTER" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRCRYSTALHUNTER">&#x201C;The Crystal Hunter&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                        (pp. 72v&#x2013;76r; 17 stanzas, entitled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>; lines numbered 1183&#x2013;1368 by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, but also 1&#x2013;115 through the beginning of stanza 11).
                                        Of the competing systems of line numbering attached to the poem, that starting at 1183 picks up from line 1182 that closes 
                                        <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRNOTSUCHTHENIGHT" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRNOTSUCHTHENIGHT">&#x201C;Not such the night whose stormy might&#x201D;</span></a>. 
                                        The alternate starting with line 1 and numbering at intervals of 5 is abandoned after stanza 11 apparently because, after stanza 12, <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> transposed stanzas. 
                                        In a letter of <span class="date-1834-02-22">22 February 1834</span>, <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> reported to his father: "Geological poem knocked up on the humps and bumps of the road, and brought to a standstill" (RFL 280).
                                    
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_address_apparatus.php#JRTHEADDRESS" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRTHEADRESS">&#x201C;The Address&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 76r&#x2013;77r; entitled &#x201C;The Address. 1834&#x201D; by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_vintage_apparatus.php#JRTHEVINTAGE" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRTHEVINTAGE">&#x201C;The Vintage&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 77r&#x2013;77v; entitled &#x201C;Continuation of Vintage&#x201D; by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_foam_globes_round_come_riding_fast_apparatus.php#JRTHEFOAMGLOBES" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRTHEFOAMGLOBES">&#x201C;The foam globes round come riding fast&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 77v3&#x2013;78r; untitled, no line numbering). 
                                        In the Library Edition, the editors assign this poem to 
                                        <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php" target="_blank">Account of a Tour on the Continent</a>, 
                                        pairing it with the prose piece, <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRSOURCEOFTHEARVERON" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRSOURCEOFTHEARVERON">&#x201C;The Source of the Arveron&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                        (Works 2:387). Given the poem&#x02BC;s placement in the MS VIII draft, this connection seems highly speculative, especially given that the lack of line numbering raises doubts 
                                        even about the poem&#x02BC;s connection to the &#x201C;Account.&#x201D; The poem&#x02BC;s meter, however, is consistent with those used in the &#x201C;Account.&#x201D;
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRHEIDELBERG3" target="_blank"><span class="title-prose-JRHEIDELBERG3">&#x201C;Cont. Heidelberg&#x201D;  &#x005B;&#x201C;Heidelberg&#x201D; prose, part 1&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 78r&#x2013;78v; prose, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li> 
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRSOBROADLYSTRETCHED" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRSOBROADLYSTRETCHED">&#x201C;So broadly stretched in sapphire sheet&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                        (p. 78v;  poem, untitled, lines numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> 1369&#x2013;76). In the Library Edition, the editors print these lines as the closing of 
                                        <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRITWASANEVEOFSUMMERMILD" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRITWASANEVEOFSUMMERMILD">&#x201C;It was an eve of summer, mild&#x201D;</span></a>&#x2014;on what grounds 
                                        they do not justify.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRHEIDELBERG4" target="_blank"><span class="title-prose-JRHEIDELBERG4">&#x201C;All has yielded to it from time immemorial&#x201D;  &#x005B;&#x201C;Heidelberg&#x201D; prose, part 3&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 78v&#x2013;79r; prose, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRGENOA2" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRGENOA2">&#x201C;Genoa&#x201D; (&#x201C;Now rouse the ho. For Genoa straight&#x201D;)</span></a> 
                                        (pp. 79r&#x2013;79v; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, lines numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> 1376&#x2013;97). 
                                        This poem incorporates <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRGENOA1" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRGENOA1">&#x201C;Genoa&#x201D; (&#x201C;Of various trees a vista green&#x201D;)</span></a> as lines 19&#x2013;44. 
                                        <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> composes new verse up to lines 19&#x2013;21, which he repeats nearly verbatim from the earlier draft, indicating the overlap with etceteras 
                                        (&#x201C;Of various trees a vista green &#x0026;c. / Into a streamlet looking down / whose living crystal shot between &#x0026;c&#x201D;). 
                                        Following line 21, he copies but then scores through the final line of the previously drafted segment (&#x201C;A little space of time&#x201D;); that is, 
                                        he omits copying, but apparently intends to include, the intervening 22 lines between the repeated opening and closing lines of the former draft&#x2014;that closing line forming 
                                        line 44 of the new &#x201C;Genoa,&#x201D; if the intervening lines are included. The join is indicated further by three <i>x</i>s above the scored line, &#x201C;A little space of time,&#x201D; 
                                        which seems to correspond to four asterisks that follow this line in the earlier draft on 64v. Following these crude directions to incorporate the earlier draft 
                                        appear three more lines that are scored through (&#x201C;And think how wide the world must be / Across from pole to pole / When all that there you look upon&#x201D;), but here the strikethrough 
                                        apparently indicates simply rejected draft. Thereafter, the poem&#x02BC;s new draft continues without interruption.
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRCADENABBIA" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRCADENABBIA">&#x201C;Cadenabbia&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                        (pp. 79v&#x2013;80v; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, lines numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> 1417&#x2013;61).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRVILLAPLINIANA" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRVILLAPLINIANA">&#x201C;Villa Pliniana&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 80v; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, lines numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> 1462&#x2013;84). 
                                        On the upper outside corners of this two&#x2010;page spread, 80v&#x2013;81r, a hand&#x2014;probably <span class="persName-WGC">Collingwood&#x02BC;s</span> (see 1891 1:266&#x2014;numbered these pages as &#x201C;p. 105&#x201D; and &#x201C;p. 106&#x201D; respectively. 
                                        This annotation accurately specifies what these pages would have been numbered had <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> carried forward with the page numbering that he left off at p. 55 
                                        (see <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php#JRIWOKETOHEARTHELULLABY" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRIWOKETOHEARTHELULLABY">&#x201C;I woke to hear the lullaby&#x201D;</span></a>). 
                                        Presumably, <span class="persName-WGC">Collingwood</span> was marking what he interpreted as the end of the &#x201C;Account&#x201D; material in MS VIII, 
                                        although, as explained previously, he was wrong in assuming that the following work, &#x201C;Saltzburg,&#x201D; belongs to an altogether later period. 
                                        The later hand (<span class="persName-AW">Wedderburn&#x02BC;s</span>?) that has numbered the folios starting with 56r struck through these two page numbers and inserted &#x201C;81&#x201D; (for 81r) above &#x201C;p 106.&#x201D;
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/saltzburg_apparatus.php#JRSALTZBURG" target="_blank"><span class="title-poem-JRSALTZBURG">&#x201C;Saltzburg&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 81r&#x2013;81v; poem, untitled in ms., lines numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/there_were_sweet_sounds_mingled_with_my_dreaming_apparatus.php#JRTHEREWERESWEET" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-prose-JRTHEREWERESWEET">&#x201C;There were sweet sounds mingled with my dreaming&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 81v&#x2013;82r; prose, untitled).
                     </li> 
                     
                     
                  </ul>
                  
               </p>
               
            </div>
            
            
            <div id="SECTIONC" class="subsection">
               <span class="head">Section <i>c</i></span>
               
               
               <p>In about <span class="date-1833-12">December 1833</span>, while drafting <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php" target="_blank">Account of a Tour on the Continent</a> in section <i>b</i>, 
                                <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> inverted MS VIII and began writing reverso, from the opposite end (on what would be pp. 162r&#x2013;64r, counting from the front of the notebook, p. 164r being the inside of the back flyleaf; 
                                for the front side of the back flyleaf, see Contents, section <i>j</i>). The <span class="date-1833-12">December</span> dating is based on 
                                <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> intending 
                                <a href="../apparatuses/the_dawn_is_breaking_on_the_bending_hills_apparatus.php#JRDAWNISBREAKING" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRDAWNISBREAKING">&#x201C;The dawn is breaking on the bending hills&#x201D;</span></a>, on evidence of its content, 
                                as a New Year&#x02BC;s ode (possibly, the following poem, 
                                <a href="../apparatuses/oh_i_must_throw_in_a_little_more_spunk.php#JROHIMUSTTHROW" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JROHIMUSTTHROW">&#x201C;Oh I must throw in a little more spunk&#x201D;</span></a>, formed part of the same project). 
                                See <a href="COLLATION">Description: Collation</a>, however, for the ambiguity in identifying which New Year this poem celebrated, whether 1832, 1833, or 1834; see also 
                                <a href="../apparatuses/once_on_a_time_the_wight_stupidity_apparatus.php#JRONCEONATIMETHEWIGHT" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRONCEONATIMETHEWIGHT">&#x201C;Once on a time the wight Stupidity &#x005B;&#x201C;The Invention of Quadrilles&#x201D;&#x005D;&#x201D;: Date.</span></a>
                  
               </p>
               
               <p>    
                  
                  <ul>
                     <span class="head">List <i>c</i></span>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/oh_quelle_odeur_apparatus.php#JROHQUELLE" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JROHQUELLE">&#x201C;Oh quelle odeur&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 164r &#x005B;i.e., inside back flyleaf&#x005D;; poem, 2 stanzas in French, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/once_on_a_time_the_wight_stupidity_apparatus.php#JRONCEONATIMETHEWIGHT" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRONCEONATIMETHEWIGHT">&#x201C;Once on a time the wight Stupidity&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;The Invention of Quadrilles&#x201D;&#x005D;</span></a> 
                                    (pp. 164r&#x2013;63v; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/it_was_as_if_awaking_from_a_dream_apparatus.php#JRITWASASIF" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRITWASASIF">&#x201C;It was as if awaking from a dream&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                    (pp. 163v&#x2013;63r; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_dawn_is_breaking_on_the_bending_hills_apparatus.php#JRDAWNISBREAKING" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRDAWNISBREAKING">&#x201C;The dawn is breaking on the bending hills&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                    (pp. 163r&#x2013;62v).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/oh_i_must_throw_in_a_little_more_spunk.php#JROHIMUSTTHROW" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JROHIMUSTTHROW">&#x201C;Oh I must throw in a little more spunk&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 162v&#x2013;62r; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/is_there_water_in_the_desert.php#JRISTHEREWATER" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRISTHEREWATER">&#x201C;Is there water in the desert&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 162r; poem, untitled, entire poem heavily scored through).
                     </li>
                     
                     
                  </ul>
                  
               </p>
               
            </div>
            
            
            
            <div id="SECTIOND" class="subsection">
               <span class="head">Section <i>d</i></span>  
               
               <p>In <span class="date-1834-12">December 1834</span>, while continuing composition in Contents, section <i>b</i> of MS VIII 
                            (and, by this time, perhaps also fair&#x2010;copying and drawing, in <a href="../apparatuses/msix_apparatus.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">MS IX</a>) of 
                            <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php" target="_blank">Account of a Tour on the Continent</a>, 
                            <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> skipped over a number of leaves, 
                            probably intending to leave space available for completion of the &#x201C;Account.&#x201D; In the new space, 
                            he entered a sequence of shorter poems, mostly celebratory odes for his father in <span class="date-1835">1835</span>, extending from poems for New Year&#x02BC;s to his father&#x02BC;s May 10 birthday. 
                            Ultimately, the gap between section <i>d</i> and the end of section <i>b</i> numbered 30 leaves; see <a href="COLLATION">Description: Collation</a>.
               </p>
               
               <p>
                  
                  <ul>
                     <span class="head">List <i>d</i></span>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/as_i_was_walking_round_by_peckham_rye_apparatus.php#JRASIWASWALKING1" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRASIWASWALKING1">&#x201C;As I was walking round by Peckham rye&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 112r&#x2013;15v; poem, untitled, 
                                17 stanzas numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/january_apparatus.php#JRJANUARY" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRJANUARY">&#x201C;January&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 114r&#x2013;14v, positioned between stanzas 11 and 12 of 
                                    <a href="../apparatuses/as_i_was_walking_round_by_peckham_rye_apparatus.php#JRASIWASWALKING2" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRASIWASWALKING2">&#x201C;As I was walking round by Peckham rye&#x201D;</span></a>, which wraps around this work; 
                                poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_fire_is_bright_the_day_is_cold_apparatus.php#JRTHEFIREISBRIGHT" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRTHEFIREISBRIGHT">&#x201C;The fire is bright the day is cold&#x201D;</span></a> 
                                    (pp. 115v&#x2013;17r; poem, untitled, 3 stanzas numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, and dated by him &#x005B;next to head of stanza 2&#x005D; <span class="date-1835-12-22">22 January 1835</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/mr_domecq_conducted_to_machernudo_apparatus.php#JRMRDOMECQ" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRMRDOMECQ">&#x201C;Mr Domecq Conducted to Machernudo by the Genius of Wine: A Dream, and No Dream&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;The skylark had folded his wing&#x201D;&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 117r&#x2013;18v; poem, untitled, 10 stanzas numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/tis_but_a_day_apparatus.php#JRTISBUTADAY" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRTISBUTADAY">&#x201C;&#x02BC;Tis but a day, or tis but a week&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 118v&#x2013;119r; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                  </ul>
                  
               </p>
               
            </div>
            
            
            <div id="SECTIONE" class="subsection">
               <span class="head">Section <i>e</i></span>     
               
               <p>As it turned out, <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> did not use the 30 leaves between sections <i>b</i> and <i>d</i> for continuation of 
                            <a href="../apparatuses/account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.php" target="_blank">Account of a Tour on the Continent</a>. Instead, the latter work being abandoned 
                            (or, more precisely, advanced to a more sophisticated level, through revision of parts for publication), Ruskin exploited this space to compose a new stint of miscellaneous works. 
                            Previously, these pieces have been associated with the family&#x02BC;s next trip to the Continent, the 
                            <a href="../notes/tour_of_1835_note.php" target="_blank" class="inactive">Tour of 1835</a>; however, as explained in <a href="COLLATION">Description: Collation</a>, 
                            <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin&#x02BC;s</span> possible motivations are complex, including his new experience as an author for the gift annuals, and the topics of these works did not necessarily hinge on first-hand experience of the places involved. 
                            Also, there is no way to determine whether <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> carried MS VIII 
                            along with him on the <span class="date-1835">1835</span> journey, except that this was likely not the case in <span class="date-1833">1833</span>.
               </p>
               
               <p>The final three items in the section <i>e</i> list have been connected with the visit by 
                            <span class="persName-ACD">Adèle Domecq</span> and her sisters to <span class="placeName-HERNE">Herne Hill</span> in <span class="date-1836-01-1836-04">early 1836</span>, 
                            but it is entirely possible that <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> composed these pieces well before this encounter 
                            (see also section <i><a href="SECTIONG">g</a></i>).
               </p>
               
               
               <p>    
                  
                  <ul>
                     <span class="head">List <i>e</i></span>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/ascent_of_the_st_bernard_apparatus.php#JRASCENTSTBERNARD" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-drama-JRASCENTSTBERNARD">&#x201C;The Ascent of the St. Bernard: A Dramatic Sketch&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 82r&#x2013;92v; prose drama, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_moon_looks_down_with_her_benignant_eyes_apparatus.php#JRMOONLOOKSDOWN" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRMOONLOOKSDOWN">&#x201C;The moon looks down with her benignant eyes&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 92v; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_palaces_shine_paly_through_the_dark_appartus.php#JRPALACESSHINEPALY" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRPALACESSHINEPALY">&#x201C;The palaces shine paly through the dark&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 92v&#x2013;92r; poem, untitled)
                     </li>
                     
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/leoni_apparatus.php#JRLEONI" target="_blank" class="inactive">&#x201C;Leoni&#x201D;</a> (pp. 93r&#x2013;103r; prose, untitled in ms.).
                     </li>
                     
                  </ul>
                  
               </p>
               
            </div>
            
            
            <div id="SECTIONF" class="subsection">
               <span class="head">Section <i>f</i></span>
               
               <p>This section is likewise conjectural, not only in terms of dating, but even in terms of sectioning off these works as a distinct group. 
                            Possibly, at about the time that <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span> was filling section <i>e</i>, or just following that time, 
                            he skipped to this section <i>f</i>, which follows section <i>d</i> 
                            with its occasional poems written in the winter of 1834&#x2013;35.
                        
               </p>
               
               
               <p>
                  
                  <ul>
                     <span class="head">List <i>f</i></span>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/avalanche_apparatus.php#JRTHEAVALANCHE" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRTHEAVALANCHE">&#x201C;The Avalanche&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 119v&#x2013;120r; poem, including prose &#x201C;note,&#x201D; untitled in ms., 8 stanzas numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>)
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/emigration_of_the_sprites_apparatus.php#JREMIGRATIONOFSPRITES" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JREMIGRATIONOFSPRITES">&#x201C;The Emigration of the Sprites&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 120v&#x2013;23r; poem, untitled in ms., 13 stanzas, of which the first 4 numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/the_forest_boughs_and_leaves_are_still_apparatus.php#JRFORESTBOUGHS" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRFORESTBOUGHS">&#x201C;The forest boughs and leaves are still&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;The Invasion of the Alps&#x201D;&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 123r&#x2013;23v; poem, untitled).
                     </li> 
                     
                  </ul>
                  
               </p>
               
            </div>
            
            
            <div id="SECTIONG" class="subsection">
               <span class="head">Section <i>g</i></span>
               
               <p>It is not clear that this section should be treated as distinct from section <i>e</i>, which precedes it. 
                            Traditionally, the section is viewed as a series of poems associated with <span class="persName-ACD">Adèle Domecq</span>. 
                            As such, the possible continuity between sections <i>e</i> and <i>g</i> points up the connection between romance such as the tale, 
                            <a href="../apparatuses/leoni_apparatus.php#JRLEONI" target="_blank" class="inactive">&#x201C;Leoni&#x201D;</a> (which, in itself, may or may not have been associated with the 
                            <a href="../notes/tour_of_1835_note.php#JRTOUROF1835" target="_blank" class="inactive">Tour of 1835</a>) and sentiment associated with <span class="persName-ACD">Adèle</span>.
                        
               </p>
               
               <p>As explained in <a href="COLLATION">Description: Collation</a>, some physical evidence does support, at least, the separation between section <i>g</i> and <i><a href="SECTIOND">d</a></i>, 
                            the latter abutted by section <i>g</i>at its end. Namely, on p. 111v, the final poem of section <i>g</i>, 
                            <a href="../apparatuses/memory_the_summer_wind_apparatus.php#JRMEMORYSUMMERWIND" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRMEMORYSUMMERWIND">&#x201C;Memory&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;The summer wind is soft and kind&#x201D;&#x005D;</span></a>, 
                            is squeezed into two parallel columns at the bottom of the page, as if to fit the poem into the space that remained on this verso, 
                            the following recto being already taken up by 
                            <a href="../apparatuses/as_i_was_walking_round_by_peckham_rye_apparatus.php#JRASIWASWALKINGROUND" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRASIWASWALKINGROUND">&#x201C;As I was walking round by Peckham rye&#x201D;</span></a>, 
                            which starts section <i>d</i>.
                        
               </p>
               
               
               <p>
                  
                  <ul>
                     <span class="head">List <i>g</i></span>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/a_dream_of_her_came_in_my_sleep_apparatus.php#DREAMSLEEP" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-DREAMSLEEP">&#x201C;A dream of her came in my sleep&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 103v; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/jacqueline_apparatus.php#JRJACQUELINE" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRJACQUELINE">&#x201C;Jacqueline&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 104r; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/come_water_the_flowers_apparatus.php#JRCOMEWATERFLOWERS" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRCOMEWATERFLOWERS">&#x201C;Come Water the Flowers&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 104v&#x2013;105r; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>, 6 stanzas numbered by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/chamois_hunters_song_apparatus.php#JRCHAMOISSONG" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRCHAMOISSONG">&#x201C;Chamois Hunter&#x02BC;s Song&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 105r&#x2013;105v; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/she_lays_her_down_in_beautys_light_apparatus.php#JRSHELAYSBEAUTY" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-SHELAYSBEAUTY">&#x201C;She lays her down in beauty&#x02BC;s light&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;Good Night&#x201D;&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 105v&#x2013;106r; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/she_sat_beside_me_yesternight_apparatus.php#JRSHESATYESTERNIGHT" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-SHESATYESTERDNIGHT">&#x201C;She sat beside me yesternight&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;The Last Smile&#x201D;&#x005D;</span></a> (p. 106r; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/swiss_maidens_song_apparatus.php#JRSWISSMAIDENSONG" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRSWISSMAIDENSONG">&#x201C;Swiss Maiden&#x02BC;s Song&#x201D;</span></a> (pp. 106r&#x2013;106v; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/oh_she_was_like_the_light_of_ruby_red_apparatus.php#JROHSHEWASLIKELIGHT" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JROHSHEWASLIKELIGHT">&#x201C;Oh she was like the light of ruby red&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 106v; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/swiss_peasants_song_apparatus.php#JRSWISSPEASANTSSONG" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRSWISSPEASANTSSONG">&#x201C;Swiss Peasant&#x02BC;s Song&#x201D;</span></a> (p. 107r; poem, titled by <span class="persName-JR">Ruskin</span>).
                     </li>
                     
                     <li><a href="../apparatuses/hast_thou_not_seen_how_the_iris_is_set_apparatus.php#JRHASTTHOUNOTSEEN" target="_blank" class="inactive"><span class="title-poem-JRHASTTHOUNOTSEEN">&#x201C;Hast thou not seen how the Iris is set&#x201D; &#x005B;&#x201C;The Iris&#x201D;&#x005D;</span></a> (pp. 107r&#x2013;107v; poem, untitled).
                     </li>
                     
